SIMPLE: hereditament
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hereditament
<hw>Her`e*dit"a*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>hereditamentum</ets>. See <er>Hereditable</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Any species of property that may be inherited;
lands, tenements, anything corporeal or incorporeal, real, personal, or
mixed, that may descend to an heir.</def>
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ A <xex>corporeal hereditament</xex> is visible and
tangible; an <xex>incorporeal hereditament</xex> is not in itself
visible or tangible, being an hereditary right, interest, or obligation,
as duty to pay rent, or a right of way.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hereditarily</ent>⟦br⟧
